4. Test the code locally
Run server
python manage.py runserver


Create a test user (if you don’t have one)
python manage.py shell


from django.contrib.auth import get_user_model
User = get_user_model()
User.objects.create_user(username="testuser", password="testpass", email="test@example.com")
exit()


Test login with curl
curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/auth/login/ \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"username": "testuser", "password": "testpass"}'


Expected response:
{
  "token": "abc123...",
  "user": {
    "id": 1,
    "username": "testuser",
    "email": "test@example.com"
  }
}


Test failure case:
curl -X POST http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/auth/login/ \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"username": "testuser", "password": "wrong"}'


You should get a 400 with an error message.
If your “5 checklist items” include things like:
- Valid credentials → token returned
- Invalid credentials → error
- Disabled user → error
- Token reused on subsequent logins
- Response matches API Contract
You can verify each with variations of the above.

